The N+1 Query Problem is a performance problem that occurs mainly in ORM frameworks like Hibernate and Spring Data JPA when fetching related data from a database.
It happens when one query is executed to fetch parent data and then N additional queries are executed to fetch related child data.
So total queries = 1 + N
________________________________________
1. Basic Idea of N+1 Problem
Suppose we have two tables:
Department
id	name
1	IT
2	HR
Employee
id	name	department_id
1	John	1
2	Mike	1
3	Sara	2
Relationship:
Department 1 ---- * Employee
________________________________________
2. Example Entities
Department Entity
@Entity
public class Department {

    @Id
    private Long id;

    private String name;

    @OneToMany(mappedBy = "department", fetch = FetchType.LAZY)
    private List<Employee> employees;
}
Employee Entity
@Entity
public class Employee {

    @Id
    private Long id;

    private String name;

    @ManyToOne
    @JoinColumn(name="department_id")
    private Department department;
}
________________________________________
3. Scenario that Causes N+1 Problem
Suppose you write this code:
List<Department> departments = departmentRepository.findAll();

for(Department dept : departments){
    System.out.println(dept.getEmployees());
}
________________________________________
4. Queries Generated
Query 1 → Fetch all departments
SELECT * FROM department;
Result:
Dept1
Dept2
________________________________________
Query 2 → Fetch employees for Dept1
SELECT * FROM employee WHERE department_id = 1;
________________________________________
Query 3 → Fetch employees for Dept2
SELECT * FROM employee WHERE department_id = 2;
________________________________________
Total Queries:
1 (departments)
+ 2 (employees for each department)

= 3 Queries
If there are 100 departments, queries become:
1 + 100 = 101 queries
This is the N+1 problem.
________________________________________
5. Why It Happens
Because of LAZY loading.
@OneToMany(fetch = FetchType.LAZY)
When departments are loaded:
employees are NOT loaded
When you access:
dept.getEmployees()
Hibernate fires another query.
________________________________________
6. Visual Flow
Application
    |
    |---- Query 1
    |     SELECT * FROM department
    |
    |---- Query 2
    |     SELECT * FROM employee WHERE dept_id=1
    |
    |---- Query 3
    |     SELECT * FROM employee WHERE dept_id=2
    |
    |---- Query 4
    |     SELECT * FROM employee WHERE dept_id=3
So the database gets many small queries instead of one optimized query.
________________________________________
7. Why It Is a Big Problem
Imagine production system:
Departments = 1000
Employees per department = 50
Queries executed:
1 + 1000 = 1001 queries
Problems:
•	High DB load
•	High network latency
•	Slow API response
•	Bad scalability
________________________________________
8. How to Solve N+1 Problem
There are 4 common solutions.
________________________________________
1️⃣ JOIN FETCH (Most common)
Use JPQL fetch join.
@Query("SELECT d FROM Department d JOIN FETCH d.employees")
List<Department> findAllDepartmentsWithEmployees();
SQL generated:
SELECT d.*, e.*
FROM department d
JOIN employee e
ON d.id = e.department_id;
Now only 1 query runs.
________________________________________
2️⃣ EntityGraph
@EntityGraph(attributePaths = "employees")
List<Department> findAll();
This tells Hibernate:
Fetch employees along with department
________________________________________
3️⃣ Batch Fetching
spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.default_batch_fetch_size=10
Instead of:
SELECT * FROM employee WHERE dept_id = 1
SELECT * FROM employee WHERE dept_id = 2
SELECT * FROM employee WHERE dept_id = 3
Hibernate will do:
SELECT * FROM employee WHERE dept_id IN (1,2,3)
________________________________________
4️⃣ DTO Projection
Instead of entities, fetch DTO.
@Query("""
SELECT new com.dto.DepartmentDTO(d.name,e.name)
FROM Department d
JOIN d.employees e
""")
This fetches everything in one query.
________________________________________
9. Difference Between Lazy vs Eager
LAZY
Department -> employees loaded later
Causes N+1.
________________________________________
EAGER
Department -> employees loaded immediately
But EAGER can cause huge joins and performance issues.
So best practice:
Use LAZY + FETCH JOIN when needed
________________________________________
10. Real Example in Production
Example API:
GET /departments
Bad implementation:
departmentRepository.findAll()
Then:
dept.getEmployees()
If there are 500 departments:
501 queries
Good implementation:
@Query("SELECT d FROM Department d JOIN FETCH d.employees")
Now:
1 query
________________________________________
11. Simple Diagram
Without Optimization

1 Query -> Departments
N Queries -> Employees

Total = N + 1
With Fetch Join

1 Query -> Departments + Employees
________________________________________
12. Important Interview Point
N+1 occurs when:
Parent entity loaded first
Child entities loaded one by one
Usually happens with:
@OneToMany
@ManyToMany
________________________________________
13. How to Detect N+1
Enable SQL logs:
spring.jpa.show-sql=true
or
logging.level.org.hibernate.SQL=DEBUG
If you see same query repeating many times, N+1 exists.
________________________________________
✅ Simple definition
N+1 problem occurs when one query loads parent entities and N additional queries load their child entities, causing serious performance issues.
